post_text: Please view the map for student car rider drop off locations. Coming from East Tallassee, pull into the drop off lane in the front of the THS main building. Coming from West Tallassee, use the drop off spot by FUMC, and students will use the crosswalk to enter THS. A crossing guard will be at this location. Students may be dropped off from 7:20-7:50 each morning. They will have the option to get breakfast from 7:20-7:45 or go straight to their first block class.

shared_text:
Pride of Tallassee Marching Band
July 1 at 8:17 AM ¬∑

Our first music rehearsal for the summer is scheduled for tomorrow.

Flutes, Clarinets, and Alto Saxes will meet from 10:00am - 11:30.

Tenor Saxes, Trumpets, Trombones, Baritones, Tubas, and Percussion will meet from 1:30 - 3:00.

You will need to wear a mask to rehearsal. You also need to bring the show music that I already passed out to you.

When you arrive on campus, please come to the front steps of the music building. Mrs. Skeen and I will take your temperature and complete a checklist before you will be allowed to stay for practice.

We will be rehearsing in the auditorium to allow for social distancing purposes.

I want to make sure we, as the band, are doing everything we possibly can to assure that we have a football and marching season this year. Please comply by wearing a mask and not standing around in groups when coming on campus tomorrow.

Looking forward to seeing all of you tomorrow!

post_text: Anslee Osborne is the daughter of Jennifer and Stephen Osborne. She started playing volleyball in the 8th grade and softball in the 7th grade. She is a member of the Leo Club, Mu Alpha Theta, Key Club, and National Honor Society. She was in the student council and served as Treasurer her junior year and Vice President during her senior year. While staying busy during her high school years, she maintained a 4.1 GPA. She attends First Baptist Church and is a member of the youth praise team. Anslee will be playing softball at Huntingdon College in the fall and has plans to become a pediatric occupational therapist. #Classof2020

post_text: We will receive guidance from Dr. Mackey and the ALSDE on Friday and next Monday. At that time we will finalize our plans for finishing out our school year. Please take recommendations for social distancing and handwashing seriously. We will overcome these circumstances!

post_text: Governor Ivey has extended the closure of Alabama Schools through the end of the school year. Tallassee City Schools has been working on plans to continue our academic year through alternative means, such as online, virtual learning and student curriculum packets.

This is what we‚Äôre sending out about serving meals.

Tallassee City Schools CNP Director, Mrs. Loria Hunter has applied for and has been approved by the Alabama Department of Education to serve meals through our school nutrition program during the times our schools are closed.

Meals will be served to all children 18 years old and under from 11:30 a.m. to noon Monday, Wednesday, and Friday. In order to adhere to health guidelines of social distancing, meals will not be consumed on site. Children will pick meals and take them home.

The following sites have been approved to begin operating the Summer Food Service Program (SFSP) effective Monday, March 30 and continue throughout the time our schools are closed:

Career Tech Center
301 Gilmer Ave

Tallassee Community Library
99 Freeman Avenue

Tallassee Sr Center/Carville Park
445 Main Street

We took all 5 concert bands to the State Music Performance Assessment this week. 6th Grade Beginner Band, 7th Grade Concert Band, 8th Grade Symphonic Band, 9th-10th Grade Concert Band, and the 11th-12th Grade Symphonic Band. With the wrestling postseason quickly approaching, Tallassee‚Äôs Zack Haynes knew he had to get back on the mats to shake off any rust before competing in this weekend‚Äôs sectional tournament. After going more than three weeks without a match due to a shoulder injury, Haynes returned to the mat last Tuesday night and pinned Pike Road‚Äôs Jacob Arnett at 126 pounds to announce his return.

‚ÄúIt was very exciting for all of us,‚Äù Tallassee coach John Mask said. ‚ÄúHe continued to work even when he was out so to see him come back with success like that was awesome.‚Äù

Haynes did not stop there as he earned two more pins during the regular-season finale, helping the Tigers to a pair of victories to finish the duals season. Haynes improved to 35-3 on the year and is the Elmore County Player of the Week.

We need as many students as possible to be a part of this trip. The total cost of the trip per person will be approx. $650. This price is for students and parents who would like to attend. The first payment of $65 is due by Feb. 28.

More details will be coming. Stay tuned.

Tallassee High School is hosting the #CapitalCityClassic this Friday and Saturday at the Montgomery Performing Arts Center! FORTY-ONE (41) choirs from Alabama, Tennessee, Mississippi, and Georgia will be there for the 12th annual show choir competition, one of the largest and most well-attended of its kind!

Auburn .. Oak Mountain .. Bumpus .. Berry .. Simmons .. Appling .. Dauphin (Enterprise) .. Opelika .. Albertville .. Helena .. Boaz .. Tift County (Georgia) .. Homewood .. Saraland .. Eufaula .. Pell City .. Chelsea .. Donelson (Tennessee) .. DeKalb (Georgia) .. Bradley Central (Mississippi) .. Lakeside (Georgia) .. Spain Park .. Cleveland (Tennessee) .. Hoover .. Jasper .. and more!

For more information, please email michael.bird@tcschools.com, kelley.hill@tcschools.com, or debbie.rogers@tcschools.com.

Tallassee's DIVAS will perform Friday night and GOLD EDITION will perform Saturday morning.

post_text:
Students returned to class on Tuesday after the two-week Christmas break. The athletic teams have remained active however.

The varsity wrestling squad competed in two tournaments during that span; the Beast at the Beach in Fort Walton, Fla. and the Julian McPhillips in Montgomery.

The Tigers took a few lumps in the Sunshine State but were up against some of the best competition in the southeast while going 3-5 over the two days in late December.

"(I'm) very proud of the team," head coach John Mask said. "The 'Beach' was a very tough tournament. I think it will help at the end of the season. Wrestling tough teams always pays of at the end."

Tallassee was third best among 18 teams at the McPhillips tourney. Four THS wrestlers placed in the top three in their weight classes; Mason Bell (154), Zak Haynes (134), Brendon Emfinger (115) and Land Bell (106).

This week, the matters will have three home matches on consecutive days before the first regional dual this weekend. Tallassee is now 18-6 on the season.

-- Michael Butler, WTLS-AM 1300 and FM 106.5

post_text:
The holidays are in the rear-view mirror as the new year is here. The advent of 2020 brings on the second season for Keiven Mixson's No. 8 ranked Tallassee Tigers basketball team. It's time for area play.

Tallassee opens the area season vs. Valley on Tuesday, Jan. 7. It will tip off a stretch of four straight area games over a nine-day stretch.

The Tigers are battle-tested with ten games vs. 6A or 7A competition. After winning the Elmore County Tournament for the second consecutive year, Tallassee put up a strong showing in Montgomery's Dwight Madison Tournament. Their record is now 15-3, but Mixson is not satisfied.

"We're not playing great," the coach said over the holiday break. "We're not peaking. We've got a long way to go. Guys are playing hard though."

Tallassee's first three area contests will be at Stumberg Gym. After the Valley game on Tuesday, the Tigers play Brew Tech on Thursday, Jan. 9 and Beauregard for Senior Night next Tuesday, Jan. 14. Tallassee travels to Valley on Jan. 16.

-- Michael Butler, WTLS-AM 1300 and FM 106.5
